# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: elmer-otto-bergman
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-davison-bailey] Bailey was born in what is now Salem Lakes, Wisconsin, son of Eugene M.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-davison-bailey] He obtained his BSc in Mechanical Engineering in 1903 from the Lewis Institute in Chicago, now Illinois Institute of Technology.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-davison-bailey] Before his graduation Bailey had started his career as draftsman at the U.S Wind Engine and Pump Company in Batavia, Illinois, and had been trouble man at the Evanston Heating Co. in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-davison-bailey] After his graduation Bailey started his lifelong career at the Chicago Edison Co., soon to be Commonwealth Edison.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-davison-bailey] From 1903 to 1905 he started as draftsman, from 1906 to 1916 he was assistant chief engineer at Fisk Street Station, and another chief engineer.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-davison-bailey] From 1921 to 1932 he was superintendent of generating stations of the company, and in 1933 appointed assistant chief operating engineer.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-davison-bailey] From 1936 to 1942 he was chief operating engineer and manager of the Super Power department.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-davison-bailey] The last years ten years at the company he was vice-president in charge of operations and engineering.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-davison-bailey] He retired on February 1, 1952 after 48 years of service.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-davison-bailey] In 1942 Bailey had been awarded the Honorary Doctor of Science by the Northwestern University.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-dow] Dow was born in Glasgow, Scotland as son of William Dow, a blacksmith, and Jean (Keppy) Dow in 1862.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-dow] He emigrated to the US in 1882 at the age of twenty.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-dow] In 1893 Dow was appointed the first plant manager of the first municipally owned power plant in Detroit, and electrical engineer for the city of Detroit.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-dow] The power plant had been built as a result of Hazen Pingree's efforts to break the power of corporations over Detroit City politics.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-dow] It was during this time that Henry Ford worked under Dow at one of the Detroit Edison substations.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-dow] Dow took Ford with him to the 1896 annual convention of the Association of Edison Illuminating Companies being held that year in New York City.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-dow] It was at this convention that Dow introduced Ford to Thomas Edison, the meeting with, and encouragement from, the great scientist becoming a great inspiration to Ford in completing his first car.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-dow] Dow was appointed water commissioner for the city of Detroit in 1916-1921 and again in 1925-1932.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-dow] In 1932, he was made the president of Detroit Edison and served until 1940.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-dow] He was elected president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers for the 1928-1929 year.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-dow] He was a member of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, American Society of Civil Engineers, American Institute of Electrical Engineers, Institute of Electrical Engineers (Great Britain), Institute of Mechanical Engineers (Great Britain).
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alex-dow] Dow also served as the President of The Engineering Society of Detroit from 1900-1901.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was born in Edinburgh, Scotland on 30 March 1851 to Edward Rupert Humphreys, an English classical scholar and profound educator, and Margaret McNutt of Prince Edward Island.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He attended his father's school in Boston after coming to the United States in 1859.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] At the age of fourteen he received an appointment and passed preliminary entrance exams for the United States Naval Academy before the academy discovered he was too young to complete entrance.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He instead began working for insurance companies and was made Secretary-Treasurer of the New York Guaranty and Indemnity Company by 1872, he became superintendent shortly thereafter.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He later became superintendent of the Bayonne and Greenville Gas Light Company and attended Stevens Institute of Technology earning his degree in mechanical engineering; he graduated in 1881.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1892 he founded Humphreys & Glasgow, Engineering, London and New York with Arthur G.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys continued his career with the Pintsch Lighting Company of New York, the United Gas Improvement Company, and the Weisbach Incandescent Gas Company.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In April 1872 he married Miss Eva Guillandeu of Bergen Point, NJ.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] They had three children in total: Harold, Crombie and Dorothy Caroline Humphreys-Turnbull.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of his son Harold, who was also the first son of a Stevens alumnus to graduate from the college, he endowed the Harold Humphreys Scholarship in 1902.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In memory of Crombie, who drowned with Harold in the Nile in 1901, the Crombie Humphreys Scholarship in 1904.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1927, Alexander Crombie Humphreys lost a battle with cancer.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] His death came two years after serving as President of his Alma mater for a quarter of a century, and chairman of the board of trustees for two years.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] The only immediate family member to outlive him was his daughter.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Following the death of Henry Morton in 1902, the board of trustees of Stevens Institute of Technology unanimously called upon Humphreys to serve his Alma mater as president.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Prior to his presidency, Humphreys was elected a trustee of the institute on 23 December 1891 and served as chair of the Stevens Alumni Association from 1883 to 1886.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys developed the institute as one of the first technical schools in the United States.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During a dinner following his inauguration, Colonel Edwin A.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, Jr., son of the school's founder Edwin A.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Stevens, presented the institute with a plot of land on which to construct a dormitory.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon assuming the office of President, Humphreys requested of Andrew Carnegie the financial support to construct a new building.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He followed this with an address to the Board of Trustees urging construction of the Morton Laboratory of Chemistry, a dormitory, a gymnasium and library – a "crying need of the Institute".
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] As a homage to his predecessor, Humphreys campaigned for the creation of the Morton Memorial Chemistry Laboratory and commissioned a book on Stevens' founding and its early years to be named in his honor.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] These initiatives were but foreshadowing of the growth Humphreys would bring to Stevens.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1924 the campus grew from just over a city block to 23-acres, enrollment quadrupled and endowment grew to $2,864,000 (from $384,800 when Humprheys took office).
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] That year also marked the successful end of the "Million Dollar Campaign", which had attracted donations from alumni as well as George Eastman and Edward Harkness.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1909, Stevens seized the opportunity to acquire Castle Point from Richard Stevens inclusive of the prominent Stevens Family Castle constructed in 1853; the purchase was primarily funded by the Carnegie Foundation and John D.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] This came within months of acquiring the land adjacent to present-day 8th street upon which fraternity houses were constructed that stand to this day.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] In 1960 the Institute expanded again and constructed two residence halls, one of which bared his name.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the growth of the institute, Alexander C.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys felt it important to impart engineering students with a sense of business – a tool that would be essential in their success in all lines of manufacturing.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] He began teaching the first courses on this topic in 1903 and is regarded as the father of Engineering Economics.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] To honor his contributions, Stevens Institute of Technology endows an Alexander Crombie Humphreys Chair in Economics of Engineering.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] During the dinner of his inauguration, Humphreys announced that one of his ambitions was to start an Honor System at Stevens to cover academic work.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Humphreys was very adamant that the creation of such a system come from the students and on the first page of the first issue of the school newspaper "The Stute" appeared an article written by a junior urging the implementation of such.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] By 1908 the students created a self run Honor Board who was charged with investigating cases, bringing up charges, judging cases by a vote and recommend punishments to the faculty.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-crombie-humphreys] Upon Humphreys' recommendation, faculty were also required to abide by such a pledge in administering exams within Honor Board guidelines on the grounds that it is a "...proviso apply[ing] to the examiner as well as to the student".
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-graham-christie] Christie was born in Manchester, Ontario, Canada to Peter Christie and Mary Honor (Graham) Christie.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-graham-christie] He obtained his MSc in mechanical engineering at the School of Practical Science at the University of Toronto in 1901.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-graham-christie] After his graduation Christie started as an apprentice in the engineering shop of the Westinghouse Machine Company.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-graham-christie] After the introduction of its first steam turbine, Christie specialized in that field.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-graham-christie] By 1909 he was research Assistant in Steam and Gas Engineering at the University of Wisconsin, and associate professor of Steam and Gas Engineering by 1914.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-graham-christie] In 1914 he moved to the Johns Hopkins University, where he became associate professor, and later Professor of Engineering until his retirement in 1948, and director of the McCoy College until 1953.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-graham-christie] In 1939-40 Christie served as president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-graham-christie] He was awarded the honorary doctor in engineering by the Stevens Institute of Technology in 1939, and by the Lehigh University in 1940.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-graham-christie] The American Society for Engineering Education awarded Christie the Lamme Gold Medal in 1948, and the first George Westinghouse Gold Medal for engineering by the ASME in 1953.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alexander-graham-christie] At the Johns Hopkins Whiting school of Engineer an annual lecture is held on his behalf, the Alexander Graham Christie Lecture.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The San Gabriel Mission was founded nearby on September 8, 1771, as part of the Spanish conquest and occupation of Alta California.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The land that would later become Alhambra was part of a 300,000-acre (120,000 ha) land grant given to Armane Gutter, a soldier from the Los Angeles Presidio.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] In 1820 Mexico won its independence from the Spanish crown and lands once ruled by them became part of the Mexican Republic.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] These lands then transferred into the hands of the United States following the defeat in the Mexican–American War.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] A wealthy developer, Benjamin Davis Wilson, married Ramona Yorba, daughter of Bernardo Yorba, who owned the land which would become Alhambra.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] With the persuasion of his daughter, Ruth, Yorba named the land after a book she was reading, Washington Irving's *Tales of the Alhambra*, which he was inspired to write by his extended visit to the Alhambra palace in Granada, Spain.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Alhambra was founded as a suburb of Los Angeles that remained an unincorporated area during the mid-19th century.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The first school in Alhambra was Ramona Convent Secondary School, built on hillside property donated by the prominent James de Barth Shorb family.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Thirteen years before the city was incorporated, several prominent San Gabriel Valley families interested in the Catholic education of their daughters established the school in 1890.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The city's first public high school, Alhambra High School, was established in 1898, five years before the city's incorporation.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] On July 11, 1903, the City of Alhambra was incorporated.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The Alhambra Fire Department was established in 1906.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Alhambra is promoted as a "city of homes", and many of its homes have historical significance.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] They include styles such as craftsman, bungalow, Spanish Mediterranean, Spanish colonial revival, Italian beaux-arts, and arts and crafts.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] There are also a large number of condominiums, rental apartments, and mixed-use residential/commercial buildings, especially in the downtown area.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Alhambra's main business district, at the intersection of Main and Garfield, has been a center of commerce since 1895.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] By the 1950s, it had taken on an upscale look and was "the" place to go in the San Gabriel Valley.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] While many of the classic historical buildings have been torn down over the years, the rebuilding of Main Street has led to numerous dining, retail, and entertainment establishments.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Alhambra has experienced waves of new immigrants, beginning with Italians in the 1950s, Mexicans in the 1960s, and Chinese in the 1980s.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] As a result, a very active Chinese business district has developed on Valley Boulevard, including Chinese supermarkets, restaurants, shops, banks, realtors, and medical offices.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The Valley Boulevard corridor has become a national hub for many Asian-owned bank headquarters, and there are other nationally recognised retailers in the city.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The historic Garfield Theatre, located at Valley Boulevard and Garfield Avenue from 1925 until 2001, was formerly a vaudeville venue and is rumored to have hosted the Gumm Sisters, featuring a very young Judy Garland.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Faded from its original glory, for its last few years it was purchased and ran Chinese-language films, and in 2001 went out of business.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Subsequently, developers have remodeled the dilapidated building, turning it into a vibrant commercial center with many Chinese stores and eateries.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] In 2003, actress Lana Clarkson was shot to death in the Alhambra home of record producer Phil Spector.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Spector lived in Alhambra's largest and most notable residence, the Pyrenees Castle, built in 1926.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] In 2009, Spector was convicted of second-degree murder in connection with Clarkson's death.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Alhambra is bordered by South Pasadena on the northwest, San Marino on the north, San Gabriel on the east, Monterey Park on the south, and the Los Angeles city neighborhoods of Monterey Hills and El Sereno on the west.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The city has a total area of 7.6 square miles (20 km2), over 99% of which is land.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Alhambra is among the communities in L.A.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] County with the highest percentage of Asian residents.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Chinese and Mexican are the most common ancestries in Alhambra.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] As of the 2020 census, Alhambra had a population of 82,868.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Its population density was 10,887.4 inhabitants per square mile (4,203.6/km2).
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] 16.4% of residents were under the age of 18 and 18.5% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] For every 100 females there were 89.5 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 87.2 males age 18 and over.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] There were 30,159 households in Alhambra, of which 27.7% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Of all households, 43.1% were married-couple households, 19.2% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 31.0% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] About 23.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 9.2% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] There were 31,466 housing units, of which 4.2% were vacant.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The homeowner vacancy rate was 0.9% and the rental vacancy rate was 3.0%.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] During 2019–2023, 17% of Alhambra residents were under 18 years old, and 19% were 65 or older.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] During 2019–2023, Alhambra had a median household income of $85,189, with 12.3% of the population living below the federal poverty line.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Approximately 42% of the city's housing units were owner-occupied as of 2019–2023.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The city is governed by a five-member city council; one member of the council is chosen as mayor.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Council members are nominated by district and elected for four-year terms.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Half of the council seats are up for election in each even-numbered year, which is held in a Tuesday after the first Monday in November during the California general election.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The City Manager is appointed by the City Council and oversees the day-to-day operations of ten City departments, 400 employees and a $145M budget.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The current City Manager, Jaylen Chcucken, was appointed in 2018, and in March 2025, the City Council, Jayden Ng, along with Pengyu Jeremy Wang and Liqian Wu extended their contract until 2031.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] In the California State Legislature, Alhambra is in the 25th Senate District, represented by Democrat Sasha Renée Pérez, who previously served as Mayor of Alhambra, and in the 49th Assembly district, represented by Democrat Mike Fong.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] In the United States House of Representatives, Alhambra is in California's 28th congressional district, represented by Democrat Judy Chu.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The San Bernardino Freeway (I-10) runs through the city's southern portions, and the Long Beach Freeway (I-710) has its northern terminus at Valley Boulevard in the far southwestern portions of the city.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Major thoroughfares within the city include Atlantic and Valley Boulevards, Mission Road, Fremont and Garfield Avenues, and Main Street.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Public transportation in Alhambra is provided by the Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority (Metro) as well as the Alhambra Community Transit.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The California High-Speed Rail Authority is considering proposals to a build high-speed rail system through Alhambra along the San Bernardino Freeway (I-10) corridor from the east city limits to west city limits.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] In late July 2010, the authority told the city that the options under consideration included building tracks down the center of the freeway and parallel to the freeway along Ramona Road.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] As proposed, there would be a 50-foot-wide (15 m) deck set on top of 35-foot-high (11 m) posts placed every 100 feet (30 m).
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The proposal is part of the high-speed rail network currently planned for California.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] It is part of the line between Los Angeles's Union Station and San Diego, through the Inland Empire.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Residents and city leaders voiced opposition to the plan to route the high-speed trains through the city in public meetings.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The independent, non-corporate community newspaper *Colorado Boulevard Newspaper* covers the city of Alhambra both in print and online, along with neighboring cities in the western San Gabriel Valley.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The *San Gabriel Valley Tribune* also covers Alhambra.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The regional daily newspaper is the *Los Angeles Times*.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The *Alhambra Post-Advocate* was the newspaper of general circulation adjudicated for the City of Alhambra and County of Los Angeles.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] It was published by the Wave Newspapers and is part of the Wave's East Edition.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Most of Alhambra's car dealerships can be found at an auto row on Main Street between Atlantic Boulevard and Raymond Avenue.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Restaurant row on Main Street is approximately between Atlantic Boulevard and Garfield Avenue.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The Hat, a local icon, was opened in Alhambra in 1951.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] It was the original, family-owned outdoor restaurant, and is now a well-known small Southern California chain.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Shakey's Pizza has a headquarters in Alhambra.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The Serbian Orthodox Eparchy of Western America has its headquarters in Alhambra.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The Alhambra Historical Society is located on Alhambra Road in a former medical office.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] In 2022, a group of dedicated members revived the organization after the long-time board dissolved.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] In 2024, it acquired the historic Story house.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Each year on Valley Boulevard, the cities of Alhambra and San Gabriel used to co-host the San Gabriel Valley Lunar New Year Parade and Festival, which ran from Del Mar to Garfield Avenues.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The event was of such significance to the majority Asian American demographic in Alhambra that it was broadcast live on Chinese radio, KWRM AM 1370, locally on KSCI-18, and later on worldwide cable and satellite TV.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Now Alhambra alone runs the event within city limits without the parade.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] From 2001 to 2008, Alhambra was the host of the Summer Jubilee, a street carnival and music concert held every Saturday, until its postponement due to loss of funds caused by the late 2000s recession.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Alhambra is home to the Los Angeles campus of Platt College and the Los Angeles Campus of Alliant International University.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The University of Southern California has a Health Sciences Alhambra campus, which hosts the university's Institute for Health Promotion and Disease Prevention Research (IPR), and its master's degree program in public health.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Almost all of the city is within the Alhambra Unified School District.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The district's public elementary and middle schools (K–8) located in Alhambra are Martha Baldwin, Emery Park, Fremont, Garfield, Granada, Marguerita, William Northrup, Park, and Ramona.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Additionally a small part of the city is assigned to Monterey Highlands K-8 in Monterey Park.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] The public high schools in Alhambra are: Alhambra High School, founded in 1898; Century High School; Independence High School; Mark Keppel High School; and San Gabriel High School (which, despite its name, is located within Alhambra).
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Historic Ramona Convent Secondary School is a Catholic all-girls college preparatory school for grades 7–12 in Alhambra.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Its first building was dedicated at Ramona Acres on January 29, 1890.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Other sectarian schools in the city include St.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Thomas More Elementary (Catholic, K–8), All Souls World Language Catholic School (Catholic, K–8), and Emmaus Lutheran (Lutheran, PK–8).
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/alhambra-california] Nonsectarian private schools include Oneonta Montessori School (grades PK–6), Sherman School (10–12), Bell Tower School (PS-5) and Leeway School (3–12).
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Founded as an engineering society focused on mechanical engineering in North America, ASME is today multidisciplinary and global.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has over 85,000 members in more than 135 countries worldwide.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME was founded in 1880 in response to numerous steam boiler pressure vessel failures by Alexander Lyman Holley, Henry Rossiter Worthington, John Edison Sweet and Matthias N.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Forney, with Robert Henry Thurston as the society's founding president.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Known for setting codes and standards for mechanical devices, ASME conducts one of the world's largest technical publishing operations.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It holds numerous technical conferences and hundreds of professional development courses each year and sponsors numerous outreach and educational programs.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Ned Djilali and Georgia Tech president and woman engineer supporter Blake R Van Leer were executive members.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Kate Gleason and Lydia Weld were the first two women members.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME is one of the oldest standards-developing organizations in America.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] It produces approximately 600 codes and standards covering many technical areas, such as fasteners, plumbing fixtures, elevators, pipelines, and power plant systems and components.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are developed by committees of subject matter experts using an open, consensus-based process.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] Many ASME standards are cited by government agencies as tools to meet their regulatory objectives.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME standards are therefore voluntary, unless the standards have been incorporated into a legally binding business contract or incorporated into regulations enforced by an authority having jurisdiction, such as a federal, state, or local government agency.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME's standards are used in more than 100 countries and have been translated into numerous languages.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The largest ASME standard, both in size and in the number of volunteers involved in its preparation, is the ASME Boiler and Pressure Vessel Code (BPVC).
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The BPVC provides rules for the design, fabrication, installation, inspection, care, and use of boilers, pressure vessels, and nuclear components.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The code also includes standards on materials, welding and brazing procedures and qualifications, nondestructive examination, and nuclear in-service inspection.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to academic journals, since 1880 the ASME has also published the magazine *Mechanical Engineering*.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] This means the nominees need not be professional educators.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] (1879–1964), an ASME Member and professor of mechanical engineering and head of the department at the Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn, established the Medal.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME runs several annual E-Fests, or Engineering Festivals, taking the place of the Student Professional Development Conference (SPDC) series.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In addition to the Human Powered Vehicle Challenge (HPVC), the Innovative Additive Manufacturing 3D Challenge (IAM3D), the Student Design Competition, and the Old Guard Competition, there are also talks, interactive workshops, and entertainment.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] These events allows students to network with working engineers, host contests, and promote ASME's benefits to students as well as professionals.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] E-Fests are held in four regions in the United States and internationally—western U.S, eastern U.S., Asia Pacific, and South America—with the E-Fest location for each region changing every year.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME holds a variety of competitions every year for engineering students from around the world.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has four key offices in the United States, including its headquarters operation in New York, N.Y., and three international offices in Beijing, China; Brussels, Belgium, and New Delhi, India.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] ASME has two institutes and 32 technical divisions within its organizational structure.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] In 1982, ASME was found to be the first non-profit organization to in violation of the Sherman Antitrust Act.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/american-society-of-mechanical-engineers] The United States Supreme Court found the organization liable for more than $6 million in *American Society of Mechanical Engineers v.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/elmer-otto-bergman] Bergman was born in 1892 in Kimball, Nebraska, the son of Andrew Bergman and Hannah (Sjoblom) Bergman.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/elmer-otto-bergman] He graduated from Kimball High School in 1909.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/elmer-otto-bergman] He started working as a teacher in the elementary schools, and served in the United States Navy for two years.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/elmer-otto-bergman] Next, Bergman started his studies at Creighton University in 1914, where he obtained his AB in 1920.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/elmer-otto-bergman] He continued his studies at the University of Colorado, where he obtained his BSc in 1925 and his MSc in 1926.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/elmer-otto-bergman] Bergman continued his studies University Colorado in Civil Engineering and obtained another AB magna cum laude and BSc with special honour in 1932.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/elmer-otto-bergman] Last he continued at Stanford University, and obtained his Doctor of Philosophy in 1938 under Stephen Timoshenko.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/elmer-otto-bergman] Bergman had started his academic career at the University of Colorado as instructor in 1924, was assistant professor from 1926 to 1932, and associate professor from 1932 to 1937.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/elmer-otto-bergman] After his graduation at Stanford University in 1938 Bergman moved into the industry.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/elmer-otto-bergman] Braun & Company, in Alhambra, California, an engineering company, which designed petroleum and chemical processing facilities and was later acquired by KBR Inc.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/elmer-otto-bergman] He started as Stress analyst, was chief research from 1940 to 1944, and staff consultant from 1944 to 1958.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/elmer-otto-bergman] In 1959 he became senior staff member at the National Engineering Science Companyin Pasadena.
[src:elmer-otto-bergman/elmer-otto-bergman] Berman was elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and served as its president in the year 1964–65.
